<h1>MATLAB Project: Nature of Solution of a Linear System</h1>

<div class="box">
    <h2>Objective</h2>
    <p>This MATLAB project determines the nature of the solution of a linear system <strong>A·x = b</strong>:  
       <ul>
           <li>Unique Solution</li>
           <li>Infinite Solutions</li>
           <li>No Solution</li>
       </ul>
       It also computes the solution(s) when they exist.
    </p>
</div>

<div class="box">
    <h2>MATLAB Code</h2>
    <p>Save this as <strong>main.m</strong>:</p>

<code>
clc; clear; close all;

% ---- Input Matrix A and vector b ----
disp('Enter matrix A:');
A = input('');
disp('Enter vector b:');
b = input('');

% ---- Check sizes ----
[m,n] = size(A);
if length(b) ~= m
    error('Vector b must have same number of rows as A');
end

% ---- Augmented matrix ----
Ab = [A b];

% ---- Compute ranks ----
rA = rank(A);
rAb = rank(Ab);

fprintf('\nRank(A) = %d\n', rA);
fprintf('Rank([A b]) = %d\n', rAb);

% ---- Determine nature of the system ----
if rA ~= rAb
    fprintf('\n➡️ The system has NO SOLUTION (Inconsistent).\n');

elseif rA == rAb && rA == n
    fprintf('\n➡️ The system has a UNIQUE SOLUTION.\n');

    % Unique solution
    x = A \ b;
    fprintf('\nSolution x:\n');
    disp(x);

else
    fprintf('\n➡️ The system has INFINITELY MANY SOLUTIONS.\n');

    % General solution using RREF
    fprintf('\nGeneral solution (RREF of augmented matrix):\n');
    R = rref(Ab);
    disp(R);
end
</code>
</div>

<div class="box">
    <h2>How It Works</h2>
    <p>The program uses rank conditions:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>rank(A) ≠ rank([A b])</strong> → No solution</li>
        <li><strong>rank(A) = rank([A b]) = n</strong> → Unique solution</li>
        <li><strong>rank(A) = rank([A b]) < n</strong> → Infinite solutions</li>
    </ul>
</div>

<div class="box">
    <h2>Example Input</h2>
<code>
A = [2 1; 3 4]
b = [3; 7]
</code>
</div>

